#include "hls_math.h"
#include "hls_stream.h"
#include "ap_fixed.h"

#define NUM_ELEMENTS 1024

typedef ap_fixed<32,10> data_t;

void linear_layer(hls::stream<data_t> &in_stream, data_t weights[NUM_ELEMENTS], data_t bias[NUM_ELEMENTS], hls::stream<data_t> &out_stream) {
    data_t in_data;
    data_t out_data = 0;

    // Perform the linear transformation for each element in the input stream
    for (int i = 0; i < NUM_ELEMENTS; i++) {
        in_data = in_stream.read();
        out_data += in_data * weights[i];
    }

    // Add bias and apply activation function
    out_data += bias[NUM_ELEMENTS-1]; // Bias added
    out_data = hls::tanh(out_data); // Tanh activation applied

    // Write the result to the output stream
    out_stream.write(out_data);
}
```

In this code, the `linear_layer` function takes three input parameters:

- `in_stream`: A streaming input for the input vector
- `weights`: A fixed array of weights for the linear transformation
- `bias`: A fixed array of bias values for the linear transformation

The function also has an output parameter `out_stream`, which is a streaming output for the final result.

The function first reads one element at a time from the input stream and multiplies it with the corresponding weight from the `weights` array. It accumulates the results of these multiplications and stores it in `out_data`. After processing all the elements, the function adds the bias value to `out_data` and applies a tanh activation function to the final result. Finally, it writes the result to the output stream.

